Jeremy Corbyn will be making his debut on Prime Minister's Questions
Since his election, Mr. Corbyn's debut at PMQ has been highly anticipated.
New chief of staff Jeremy Corbyn will make his debut on Prime Minister's Questions later, and for the first time he will be working with David Cameron.
Mr Corbyn will ask the first of his six assigned questions shortly after noon, while his performance is likely to be closely scrutinized by the media and MPs.
In his weekly statement, he called for "less theater and more facts".
He also mentioned that he might skip a few sessions that he would leave to his colleagues.
This meeting will be the first parliamentary test of Mr. Corby's leadership, coming after his appointment to the shadow cabinet and his speech Tuesday to the TUC annual convention.
Meanwhile, the Labour leader's decision to stand silent during the singing of the national anthem at the service on Tuesday to mark the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Britain has been criticised by a number of Conservative MPs and has been the focus of several headline stories.
Mr. Corbyn's decision not to sing the national anthem has attracted attention
Mr Corbyn's spokesman said he would "stand in reverential silence" and acknowledge "the heroism of the Royal Air Force in the Battle of Britain".
However, a member of Mr Corbyn's shadow cabinet, Owen Smith, told BBC Two's Newsnight programme that he would recommend the Labour leader sing the national anthem "regardless" of his belief that the monarchy should be abolished.
Nearly a dozen shadow ministers refused to serve on Mr. Corbyn's top team, citing differences in the economy, defense and foreign affairs, and only less than a sixth of the parliamentary party originally supported him as leader.
BBC political correspondent Robin Brant says political differences at work are also "squatting" after Mr Corbyn's appointment over his position in the European Union and the government's benefit cap.
Mr Corbyl said at the TUC conference that the Labour Party had put forward amended proposals to remove the whole idea of a benefit limit.
A few hours later, Mr Smith, the Shadow Secretary for Work and Pensions, said the party had "very clearly" opposed government plans to reduce the limit from £26,000 to £23,000.
Mr Corbyn will be the fifth Labour leader to face David Cameron in the decade since his election as leader of the Conservatives.
The Labour leader, who has promised a different approach to politics, claims to have ideas "from the crowd" for questions for Mr Cameron and has received over 30,000 suggestions.
Islington North MP argues that the PMQs are too confrontational and that they will refrain from both "casual responses" and "dental trade", and instead pledges to focus on important issues such as poverty, inequality and the challenges facing young people.
Mr Corbyn claims that Angela Eagle, the shadow trade secretary, will represent him at PMQ when he is not attending, as for example when Mr Cameron travels abroad.
He also dropped the idea of letting his colleagues speak for him from time to time, because he was told he was still discussing the matter with Speaker John Bercow.
When Mr Cameron became leader in 2005, he said he wanted to move away from the "Punch and Judy" style of politics that was often associated with PMQ, but admitted years later that it had failed.
Since its first broadcast in 1990, the PMQs have been seen as a key barometer of the judgement of leaders, their leadership of the House and their standing among other MPs, although critics have argued that they have become a caricature and far-reaching reforms are needed.
