Multiple sclerosis: it's not just the medication that matters, it's the patient's will to fight.
Multiple sclerosis is a complicated disease, and a person diagnosed with it needs the care of a number of specialists: a neurologist, a physiotherapist, an occupational therapist, a urologist, an ophthalmologist, a psychologist, a psychiatrist, and many other specialists.
It is not just about medical care, for example, women with multiple sclerosis also need consultation if they decide to have a child, care for these patients includes social and legal advice, recommendations for housing adjustments, etc.
However, this is not enough: the development of the disease can be significantly influenced by the patient himself.
The more actively he fights the disease, the longer he can work and the less he will have to make any major changes in his lifestyle.
As doctors warn, the passivity of the sick leaves room for disease activity.
For example, regular exercise has been shown to greatly delay the time when a patient needs some compensatory aid, such as a cane.
It is important that patients and those around them not be subjected to myths, such as that their illness automatically leads to their being in a wheelchair.
This is why the website Give Yourself a Chance (www.bezmytu.cz) was created, which is supported by the ongoing media campaign Give Yourself a Chance.
The most important person in the care of a person with multiple sclerosis is the neurologist.
The proverb about multiple sclerosis is twofold: The sooner the disease is treated, the more likely it is that the doctor can make a difference.
That's because we have drugs for MS in the inflammatory stage, when the neurodegeneration process isn't quite as strong yet.
The earlier we intervene, the greater the chance of stopping the disease and delaying its disabling effects, explains Dr. Eva Medová of the Neurological Clinic of the General Faculty Hospital in Prague.
Rehabilitation care is very important for people with multiple sclerosis, which most often addresses weakness of the lower limbs or imbalances.
Patients are treated according to their individual needs: to maintain fitness, improve walking, strengthen the pelvic floor, alleviate swallowing disorders, or improve coordination.
"It's really individual, it depends on the specific problems of the patient", says Dr. Martina Kövári, head of the Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine Clinic at the Faculty Hospital in Motol.
Although people with multiple sclerosis have the same disease, each person has a slightly different manifestation of the disease.
Rehabilitation can't stop the disease, but it can always ease its symptoms.
However, physical activity also strengthens the body's immune system, which is desirable in the case of multiple sclerosis.
Another positive aspect of regular exercise is that it helps patients to test their abilities, which increases their confidence.
"Exercise also releases endorphins and makes you feel good", notes Dr. Kamila Rassová of the Rehabilitation Medicine Clinic at the Royal Hospital of Vinohrady.
By affecting the physical side, we're affecting the limbic system, which is responsible for emotions.
It's how we intervene in the psyche and the immune system and stabilize the disease, he adds.
"Previously these patients were so-called self-screened, now we know that they need targeted care", says Prof. PaedDr. Pavel Kolář, head of the Rehabilitation and Exercise Medicine Clinic at the Faculty Hospital in Motol.
The aim of physical therapy is to keep a person self-sufficient for as long as possible, including employment.
Physical therapists work with occupational therapists to provide each person with a compensatory aid tailored to his or her needs.
Many patients also need the attention of a psychologist or psychiatrist.
They're in a tough situation.
When a serious illness comes into your life, most people are shocked.
They're in shock, panic, fear.
They have to respond to a big burden - the loss of health.
With a soul this sick, we're supposed to go to someone, not try to carry it all on our own.
"I work with them so that they eventually come to the conclusion that even with a disability, one can live a full life and that multiple sclerosis is not the end of life", says psychotherapist Renata Malinová-Schubert of the Neurological Clinic of the General Faculty Hospital in Prague.
Without Latecoere, the Prague manufacturer, the airbuses would not fly.
Aerospace is synonymous with precision and advanced technology.
New planes are full of titanium or lightweight, solid composite materials that no one can make and process right away.
Yet, besides super-precise, computer-controlled machinery, besides the autoclaves for forming composites, you can come across something as simple as a meringue oven.
In a drum resembling a cotton-sugar pot, the edges of tin pieces that have just come out of the mill are rubbed together in a pile of ovens.
"Nobody has come up with anything better", smiles Ivan Dubský, CEO of the Czech manufacturer of flight doors Latecoere.
At the Prague facility in Letňany, the former Fotov manufactures complete doors for the Airbus A320.
