They're also assembling a door full of composites for the new Boeing 787 Dreamliner.
Accuracy is the motto here.
Like the company has the keys sorted twice a year.
If the yellow label was missing a check record, they would have to explain it to the auditors at the Prague plant from Airbus or Boeing, who regularly check that the doors are manufactured according to the agreed rules.
But advanced technology has not yet completely replaced the human senses.
There are 1,500 knots on one door of the A320.
The gunners have to unlock them manually.
It takes them two days.
Even the sound of a hammer when it hits the net will tell if the net has been properly untied.
The tolerance in which they move is minimal.
The wire may rise above the surface of the aircraft from zero to 0,13 mm.
That's about twice the thickness of a human hair.
The check will involve a trained touch.
When the controller passes his finger over a series of nuts, he can tell if any are out of tolerance.
Then he'll pick up the accurate deflector.
