Members of Parliament have supported a larger share of the state's coal tax.
The change in mineral extraction fees is expected to bring 427 million crowns more into the state treasury than in 2013.
The government claims that the tax is to have a neutral impact on the revenue of the municipalities' budgets, as the charge is to be higher.
In the previous year, municipalities received about CZK 450 million from fees and the state budget CZK 150 million.
The municipality received about 200 million crowns and the State 66 million crowns from the extraction of brown coal.
The amendment also provides for an increase in the remuneration of occupied land with permitted mining to one thousand crowns per hectare per year.
The revenue from these payments shall remain fully owned by the municipalities.
Industry Minister Jan Mládek (ČSSD) told MPs that municipalities would benefit from the scheme by earning between 14 million and 100 million crowns annually instead.
The amount of mining fees will no longer be determined by law, but will be determined by the government by its own decree.
The remuneration shall be recalculated as the product of the quantity of ore extracted and the rates for each type of ore.
According to the Government, the reason for the change is, inter alia, the possibility of a flexible response to the current economic situation.
But ODS MP Marek Benda warned that the imposition of a fee by government decree may not be in line with the constitution.
According to the Minister, however, this is not a tax, because the state charges a tax on the mineral, which is state property.
Only the municipalities whose territory is affected by the mining activity receive the fees.
In the case of deep coal mining, three-quarters of the money goes to the municipality and one-fourth to the state.
The same ratio will apply to the extraction of radioactive rock.
The part of the money collected by the State from the extraction fees will be assigned to a specific purpose.
For example, 28 percent will have to go to repair damage after mining or to provide a mining rescue service.
The bill was criticized by opposition lawmakers, who said it would damage mining communities and regions.
For example, Michal Kucherera (TOP 09 and Mayor) warned that mining companies would no longer want to sponsor municipalities as they have done so far, because they would pay higher fees directly to the state budget.
"It is not possible to tunnel one of the poorest regions just so that the finance minister can improve the budget", said David Kádner (Usvit), elected in the Usteck region.
The increase in unemployment in Mostecka was warned by KSČM MP Hana Aulická.
Kádner and Aulická unsuccessfully proposed to reject the amendment, Kucher wanted to return the law to the government for finishing.
The explanatory memorandum states that according to the mining companies, the increase in fees will not be reflected in the coal prices, since more than 90% of the prices are negotiated in the long term.
The main consumers such as power plants or heat plants should therefore not be affected by the price increase.
'On the other hand, this fact increases the risk that mining organisations will compensate for the increase in remuneration by trying to reduce their operating costs, which would primarily mean a reduction in the number of employees,' the Government admits.
However, it considers that the increase in fees is tolerable from the point of view of employment.
