 Sonogenetics or control of brain cells by sound waves
This video shows how sound pulses affect the direction in which the spider is moving.
Scientists have bred worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can control sound waves.
The tiny gills change direction when they are struck by sound pulses that are inaudible to the human ear.
The pulses work by switching on the cells of genetically modified motor neurons that are programmed to respond to these ultrasound waves.
Related: Scientists can read and record brain activity using light
The researchers said that these worms are a great example of a new methodology called sonogenetics, which uses ultrasound to activate brain, heart, and muscle cells and activates them outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that this method could one day replace deep brain stimulation, an invasive procedure in which electrodes are inserted into the patient's brain to stimulate the brain, which is used, for example, to treat the symptoms of Parkinson's disease.
The glands don't normally respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that a reaction occurs when they are placed in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
He found that the bubbles amplify the ultrasonic waves that then pass through the worms' bodies.
The amplified ultrasound waves act in the TRP-4 ion channels, which are found in the membranes of some worm cells.
Sound waves open these channels and activate the cells to which they are attached, reports the journal Nature Communications.
In order to control the larvae with ultrasound waves, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motor neurons contained TRP-4 ion channels.
When he then applied ultrasound to the modified worms, the sound waves were amplified by the microbubbles and transmitted to the worms, where they activated the modified motor neurons.
The new method is similar in many ways to optogenetics, a pioneering tool that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off with light.
However, Chalasani has been told that sonogenetics could have many advantages over this technique.
Unlike light, which must be sent by optical fiber to a desired location in the brain, ultrasound waves can penetrate tissues without restriction and be sent directly to the brain.
"We believe that by using gene therapy and therapeutic viruses, we can target human neurons and make them temporarily sensitive to the ultrasound signals used in clinical therapy to treat neurological diseases", Chalasani said.
He added that the method could also be applied to muscle cells and insulin-producing cells.
