Apple has a yo-yo effect.
It's all the screens.
A more powerful processor, a higher-resolution camera, a more robust chassis, or a touch-sensitive display - these are, in short, the advantages of the recently introduced ninth-generation iPhones.
The latter two also have a negative impact on the size and weight of the iPhone 6s and 6s Plus.
The trend at Apple so far has been that each new generation of iPhone is lighter than the previous one.
The only exceptions were the third and fourth generation iPhones, which had slightly increased in weight compared to previous iPhones.
The difference of two grams in weight, to the detriment of the novelties, was really negligible.
But that's not the case with the new iPhones.
Compared with last year's iPhones 6 and 6 Plus, the smaller model has gained 14 grams, and the larger one has gained 20 grams.
On the one hand, it's no wonder that last year's Apple pocket flip affair was a huge hit.
The chassis of the new model is made of a more durable 7000 aluminium alloy, which also reflects the weight.
But the screen has a much bigger impact on her.
Apple's newest technology is 3D Touch, which allows displays to detect the force of touch.
To do this, the display had to be fitted with an additional layer of capacity sensors.
The new iPhones have more than doubled the screen weight of previous generations.
The smaller iPhone went from 12 grams to 29 grams, and the larger iPhone went from 19 grams to 40 grams.
So the iPhone 6s, the display is the heaviest component used.
The weight of just 143 grams is achieved by the de-fattening of most of the other components.
The heaviest component used in the larger model is the battery, but its weight has not changed from the previous model.
Again, the biggest increase is in the display.
The weight of the 5.5" iPhone 6s Plus is 192 grams.
As far as new display technology is practical, it will only show up when you use it.
The first users will be able to try it out as early as Friday, September 25, when the iPhone 6s and 6s Plus will go on sale in selected countries.
Have cereal been the breakfast of champions for tens of thousands of years?
In the Italian Grotta Paglicci, archaeologists have made a discovery that opens up interesting possibilities.
They found traces of modern human habitation from different eras, including murals, remnants of tools, and so on and so forth.
But in layer 23A, which the instruments date back to about 30,000 years ago, scientists have discovered something that looks very much like the remains of a breakfast buffet.
The traces of oat grain were found at the site, which apparently went through the process of making the flour that is so popular today.
In this way, the grain is first soaked, then dried, stripped of the covering, called the pollen, then heated and the surface polished.
Grain was discovered in the Paglicci cave, which was apparently heated or steamed, and then probably crushed between two millstones - at least this is indicated by the use of traces on two stones in the cave.
So the researchers, in their publication for the journal PNAS, were unable to prove that the cave had a complete process for making flakes, but the similarity is indeed very striking.
We also have no evidence of how people could eat the cereal, but the idea that it was with some liquid and quite possibly heat, of course, makes perfect sense.
It is also a very interesting evidence of how intensively people used grain long before agriculture was invented.
If the flour interpretation is correct, the oldest flour predates agriculture by about 20,000 years.
