In their most anticipated session in years, Federal Reserve lawmakers will spend two days this week sitting at the 27-foot-long Honduran Mahogany table deciding whether it's time to raise the key interest rate after nearly a decade.
Perched above them at one end of the central bank's ornament, the two-story boardroom will be a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues are to put the nation's economic interests above all else.
The Fed has a double mandate from Congress: maximize American employment and keep prices stable here.
But since the Great Recession, Fed officials have recognized that there is an unwritten third term: financial stability.
And this third term could be the X-factor too close to a predictable decision to be announced on Thursday about whether the US economy is ready to kick in as it departs from the unprecedented stimulus of near-zero short-term interest rates in place since the end of 2008.
While most data shows solid economic growth, the recent turbulence in global financial markets could scare the already cautious Fed into adding to the volatility by raising its federal funds rate - by no more than a quarter of a percentage point.
"It's clear that the labor market and inflation will be the most important thing to watch", said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"But I think they were just looking for an excuse not to increase the rate, the increased uncertainty surrounding the global market already gives them sufficient justification to wait further", she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself is a cause of nervousness in the financial markets.
About half of the economists recently surveyed by Bloomberg predicted a rate hike this week.
However, financial markets expect the Fed to delay the issue, with the key indicator only around a 30% chance of rising.
This would indicate a decline in the stock market if the Fed raises rates, only if politicians soften the blow by promising that further increases are imminent.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average jumped 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The meeting was triggered by the expectation that Fed politicians would keep rates low this week, says John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be a surprise if the Fed raised rates now", he says.
If Fed politicians did, "they would have to go to the extreme in their program statement and hold the financial markets in hand to avoid panic".
Other experts argued that raising rates would calm financial markets, as it would remove uncertainty about how the Fed would proceed.
Just a month ago, it seemed that the Fed was on track to raise rates by 0.25 percentage point this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the economic recovery in the US.
Yellen said she expects to see a rate hike this year through the spring and early summer despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress is needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, the labour market has recorded solid growth this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to what the Fed considers full employment.
Wage gains showed signs of improvement.
And while inflation continues to fall below the central bank's annual 2% target, Fed politicians argue that the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "can and needs to cope with higher rates, given the tightness of the labor market", said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world began to falter late last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell as much as 16% below its record high in May as investors feared that a slowing Chinese economy would drag down global growth.
The market has rebounded somewhat this month and the Dow is now only losing almost 10% of its May high.
The volatile market situation gives the Fed a complex calculation of when to start raising interest rates.
"In the absence of what's happened in the financial markets, and the reports of weakness in the Chinese economy over the past few weeks, there would be a tightening up at this meeting", said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior research fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official.
Now he predicts they'll wait at least a month to get better control of the consequences.
"There's a lot of uncertainty about how this will affect the U.S. economy, and they have almost no reliable data on the latest developments in China", Oliner said.
The health of the global economy is not one of the Fed's top concerns, so technically it shouldn't be included in their decision-making.
But in fact, the Fed has become the monetary authority of the entire world.
The central bank's influence in recent years has been enormous.
The mere hint by then-chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed might "squeeze" their monetary expansion in the market, set off convulsions around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly interconnected, it is to be expected that Fed officials will monitor developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central bankers and experts to better read the state of the global economy.
Their decision-making process is "more art than science", said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy for wealth-management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., noted this month that "The Fed has a history of exaggerated moves in financial markets that seem unrelated to economic fundamentals".
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee, which pushed for higher rates, cited the 1998-99 decision as an example.
The financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to cut its benchmark rate by 0.75 percentage point during three sessions "despite limited identifiable impacts on U.S. growth", Lacker said.
