For moderately obese diabetics, weight loss surgery may be helpful
The weight loss benefits of surgery for moderately obese people with type 2 diabetes may last for at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is too early to say whether moderately obese people with type 2 diabetes live longer after weight-loss surgery than those receiving nonsurgical treatment.
"The mortality data take a long time to come out", says Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in weight-loss surgery who wrote the editorial for a new JAMA surgery study.
Weight loss surgery, bariatric surgery, they use different methods to shrink the stomach.
Reducing hunger and limiting the human body's absorption of food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proven effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most of the research has been done on morbidly obese people with a body mass index (BMI) of 25 or higher.
BMI, which measures the ratio of weight to height, is considered normal at values between 18,5 and 24,9.
A BMI of 25 or higher indicates that a person is overweight, and people over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For their new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected from a 2007 study that looked at two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and gastrectomy - in treating type 3 diabetes procedures in people who were moderately obese.
The average BMI of those who underwent surgery fell from 31 to 24.5 by the end of their fifth year, according to the study.
Meanwhile, the BMI of those who did not receive surgical treatment for diabetes remained roughly the same at 29.
Among the surgical patients, diabetes was completely resolved in 36 percent and partially resolved in 28 percent.
In the treatment group, only about 1% of patients had complete and only about 2% had partial resolution of diabetes.
Furthermore, control of blood pressure, triglycerides, and "bad" LDL cholesterol was shown to be "generally better in the surgical group", the authors found.
The researchers also monitored the patient's blood hemoglobin A1c, which reflects the body's current blood sugar level.
The best way to keep hemoglobin A1c below 7 percent, researchers report.
After surgery, the average hemoglobin A1c decreased from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
However, in the treatment group, this figure remained at about 8 percent.
But this better "glycemic control" - reflected in better hemoglobin A1c levels - did not reduce mortality at five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and his colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results of two types of surgery.
After five years, the bypass group lost more weight compared to the gastrectomy group (18.7 kg vs. 14.2 kg), had greater decreases in BMI (7.4 vs. 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1 percent vs. 2.1 percent), and were more likely to have diabetes remission (46.9 percent vs. 16.7 percent).
While the new study does not show improvements in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of stronger people in Sweden, where they found that surgery leads to longer life, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona College or Medicine-Phoenix.
