Xi calls for opening up the economy to the wider world
It is necessary to open the economy to the wider world to boost growth, President Xi Jinping told the management reform task force on Tuesday.
"China should engage in attracting foreign investment and expertise and improve open policies", he said of the 16th meeting of the Central Leadership Group on Deepening Comprehensive Reform.
The promotion of opening-up in the emerging reforms will add new momentum and vitality, and will also provide new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The Steering Group adopted a number of directives, including a negative list on regulatory market access, the liberalisation of border controls, the encouragement of State-owned enterprises (SOEs) to absorb private capital and the reorganisation of the resident registration system.
The declaration states that a negative list will be drawn up identifying sectors and enterprises that are outside the investment threshold.
This system will be tested and improved through test programmes.
The Commission notes that the Commission has not yet adopted a decision on the compatibility of the aid with the internal market.
The government will also ease controls on the powers it delegates to firms, and ensure that firms themselves decide how to run their businesses.
The statement also states that China will enable the border regions to discover new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to support regional growth.
In an effort to open up the state-controlled sector, more areas will be opened up to private investment.
"The government will not change its foreign investment policy and will protect the legitimate interests of companies that are financed from abroad and provide them with better services", the statement said.
In addition, it will be easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or a 'green card', by streamlining the requirements and simplifying the application process.
The meeting also discussed ensuring the rights of lawyers to practise and to develop professional judges and prosecutors.
The meeting was also attended by Premier Li Keqiang and the Heads of State Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, according to a statement issued after the meeting.
In the Karlovy Vary region, a new bed unit may be created.
According to the Deputy Headman of Karlovy Vary region, Jakub Panik (ČSSD), the current capacity of the bed departments of two regional hospitals and two private hospitals in the region is sufficient and partial adjustments should be made on the basis of an agreement between the departments of individual hospitals.
There are also opportunities to expand care in the region.
For example, a one-day surgery centre could be set up in a surgical department, where surgical procedures that do not require hospitalization for more than 24 hours would be performed according to the concept.
It is not yet clear in which specific hospitals the one-day surgery workplace should be.
A laser centre could be set up in the skin department of Karlovy Vary Hospital, with the possibility of applying laser technology to skin diseases.
The concept also recommended the creation of an apalic center to care for patients with brain damage who are in a vegetative state.
Such a centre should be centrally established and should be an integral part of the anaesthesia and resuscitation unit.
There is also the possibility of concentrating such a facility in the Ostrov hospital, where similar care already exists.
Another bed capacity that appears to be insufficient in the Karlovy Vary region is the aftercare beds, in particular the Long-Term Care (LDN) bed, which is insufficient in Nejdek and should closely follow the acute care beds.
Part of the facility should function as a rehabilitation bed and part as a conventional LDN bed, the concept suggests.
He points out that the aftercare beds are missing mainly at Karlovy Vary Hospital.
There's a lot of abandoned buildings that could be used after the re-location.
Last but not least, there are no social health beds in the Karlovy Vary region, which focus on the treatment of Alzheimer's disease.
There is a shortage of these beds throughout the republic, so it could serve other regions as a so-called Alzheimer's center.
The recommendation also calls for hospitals to prepare for the introduction of so-called 'spare beds' to which European grants will be made available.
"These beds will follow up on the super-specialized care areas and will provide a space for patients to be transferred after surgery, for example after cardiac surgery, neurosurgery, transplantation or other procedures", the regional concept of bed care describes.
New services could also be offered in the field of psychiatric care.
